[[Major League Soccer]] |date=19 September 2018 |access-date=20 September 2018 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921000422/https://matchcenter.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter/2018-09-19-toronto-fc-vs-tigres-uanl/stats |archive-date=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:80px\" | Toronto FC\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:80px\" | UANL\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Goals scored\n| 1\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Total shots\n| 15\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Shots on target\n| 4\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Saves\n| 1\n| 3\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Ball possession\n| 48%\n| 52%\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Corner kicks\n| 6\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Fouls committed\n| 14\n| 11\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Offsides\n| 0\n| 2\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Yellow cards\n| 0\n| 0\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Red cards\n| 0\n| 0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.campeonescup.com/}}\n\n{{Campeones Cup}}\n{{2018\u201319 in North and Central America, and Caribbean football (CONCACAF)}}\n{{Toronto FC matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campeones Cup 2018}}\n[[Category:Campeones Cup|2018]]\n[[Category:2018 in American soccer]]\n[[Category:2018 in Canadian soccer]]\n[[Category:2018\u201319 in Mexican football]]\n[[Category:Toronto FC matches]]\n[[Category:Tigres UANL matches]]\n[[Category:International sports competitions in Toronto]]\n[[Category:September 2018 sports events in Canada]]\n[[Category:2010s in Toronto]]\n[[Category:International club association football competitions hosted by Canada]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Campeones_Cup"}
{"title_page": "The Uninhabitable Earth", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 magazine article}}\n[[File:The_Uninhabitable_Earth_-_cover.jpg|right|thumb|Cover page of ''The Uninhabitable Earth'']]\n'''\"The Uninhabitable Earth\"''' is a ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine article by American journalist [[David Wallace-Wells]] published on July 9, 2017. The [[Long-form journalism|long-form article]] depicts a [[worst-case scenario]] of what might happen in the near-future due to [[global warming]]. The article starts with the statement \"[i]f your anxiety about global warming is dominated by fears of sea-level rise, you are barely scratching the surface of what terrors are possible.\"  The story was the most read article in the history of the magazine, according to Wallace-Wells.<ref name=\"NYJ\">{{cite web |url=https://journalism.nyu.edu/about-us/event/2017-fall/the-doomed-earth-controversy/ |title=The \u2018Doomed Earth\u2019 Controversy |work=Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute |author=Robert Lee Hotz |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=March 31, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe article was the inspiration for [[The Uninhabitable Earth (book)|''The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming'']], a book-length treatment of the ideas explored in the original essay.<ref>{{ASIN|B07GVPFH5V}}</ref>\n\n==General==\nOn November 20, 2017, NYUs Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute hosted a 2 hour long conversation between Wallace-Wells and Michael E. Mann to discuss the controversy around the article.<ref name=\"NYJ\"/>\n\nAccompanying the article are a series of extended interviews with scientists. These include paleontologist [[Peter Ward (paleontologist)|Peter Ward]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/what-mass-extinctions-teach-us-about-climate-change-today.html |title=\u2018The Models Are Too Conservative\u2019: Paleontologist Peter Ward on What Past Mass Extinctions Can Teach Us About Climate Change Today |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> climatologist [[Michael E. Mann]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/scientist-michael-mann-on-climate-scenarios.html |title=Scientist Michael Mann on \u2018Low-Probability But Catastrophic\u2019 Climate Scenarios |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]  |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> oceanographer [[Wallace Smith Broecker]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/man-who-coined-global-warming-on-worst-case-scenarios.html |title=The Man Who Coined the Term \u2018Global Warming\u2019 on the Worst-Case Scenario for Planet Earth |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref> climatologist [[James Hansen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/scientist-jim-hansen-the-planet-could-become-ungovernable.html |title=\u2018The Planet Could Become Ungovernable\u2019: Climate Scientist James Hansen on Obama\u2019s Environmental Record, Scientific Reticence, and His Climate Lawsuit Against the Federal Government |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 12, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref> and scientist [[Michael Oppenheimer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/michael-oppenheimer-10-percent-chance-we-meet-paris-targets.html |title=\u2018Personally, I Would Rate the Likelihood of Staying Under Two Degrees of Warming As Under 10 Percent\u2019: Michael Oppenheimer on the \u2018Unknown Unknowns\u2019 of Climate Change |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 13, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref> In addition an annotated edition of the article was published online that includes inline footnotes.\n\nIn February 2019, Wallace-Wells published ''The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming'' ({{ISBN|978-0525576709}}).<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/586541/the-uninhabitable-earth-by-david-wallace-wells/9780525576709/ |title=The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming |publisher=Penguin RandomHouse |author=David Wallace-Wells |isbn=9780525576709 |year=2019 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> The book was excerpted in ''The Guardian''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/feb/02/the-devastation-of-human-life-is-in-view-what-a-burning-world-tells-us-about-climate-change-global-warming |title=\u2018The devastation of human life is in view\u2019: what a burning world tells us about climate change  |work=[[The Guardian]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=February 2, 2019 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe story received immediate criticism from the climate change community along two fronts: the piece is too pessimistic; or it contains some factual errors.<ref name=drum>{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2017/07/our-approach-to-climate-change-isnt-working-lets-try-something-else/ |title=Our Approach to Climate Change Isn\u2019t Working. Let\u2019s Try Something Else. |work=Mother Jones |author=Kevin Drum |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRobinson Meyer of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said it is an \"unusually specific and severe depiction of what global warming will do to the planet.\"<ref name=meyer>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/07/is-the-earth-really-that-doomed/533112/ |title=Are We as Doomed as That ''New York'' Magazine Article Says? |work=[[The Atlantic]] |author=Robinson Meyer |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Susan Matthews writing in ''Slate'' said \"The instantly viral piece might be the ''[[Silent Spring]]'' of our time\".<ref name=matthews>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2017/07/we_are_not_alarmed_enough_about_climate_change.html |title=Alarmism Is the Argument We Need to Fight Climate Change |work=Slate |author=Susan Matthews |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe NGO [[Climate Feedback]] summarized reviews by dozens of professional scientists and concluded the majority of the reviewers tagged: Alarmist, Imprecise/Unclear, Misleading.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://climatefeedback.org/evaluation/scientists-explain-what-new-york-magazine-article-on-the-uninhabitable-earth-gets-wrong-david-wallace-wells/ |title=Scientists explain what New York Magazine article on \"The Uninhabitable Earth\" gets wrong |work=Climate Feedback |author= |date=July 12, 2017 |accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome journalists defended the science saying it is mostly correct, \"I haven\u2019t seen any good evidence for serious factual errors,\" said Kevin Drum.<ref name=drum/> Emily Atkin said \"The complaints about the science in Wallace-Wells\u2019s article are mostly quibbles\".<ref name=atkin>{{cite web |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/143788/power-peril-climate-disaster-porn |title=The Power and Peril of \"Climate Disaster Porn\" |work=New Republic |author=Emily Atkin |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe major criticism is that David Wallace-Wells was trying to scare people.<ref name=drum/> This theme was then explored by journalists and commentators with some saying they thought fear was necessary given the reality of the problem, while others thought scaring people was counter-productive.<ref name=meyer/><ref name=matthews/><ref name=drum/><ref name=atkin/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-energy-202/2017/07/11/the-energy-202-trump-could-start-his-infrastructure-push-at-energy-department/59638f59e9b69b7071abcaf2/ |title=The Energy 202: Trump could start his infrastructure push at Energy Department |work=[[Washington Post]] |author=Dino Grandoni |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> For example, [[Eric Holthaus]] said that \"scaring the shit out of [people] is a really bad strategy\" for getting them to want to [[Climate change mitigation|address climate change]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grist.org/climate-energy/stop-scaring-people-about-climate-change-it-doesnt-work/ |title=Stop scaring people about climate change. It doesn\u2019t work. |work=Grist |author=Eric Holthaus  |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a later interview, David Wallace-Wells said \"it didn\u2019t seem plausible to me that there was more risk at scaring people too much than there was at not scaring them enough ... my feeling was, and is, if there's a one percent chance that we\u2019ve set off a chain reaction that could end the human race, then that should be something that the public knows and thinks about.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://gothamist.com/2017/07/10/climate_change_ny_mag.php |title=Are Humans Doomed? A Q&A With The Author Of NY Mag's Terrifying Climate Change Story |work=Gothamist |author=Rebecca Fishbein |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710230334/http://gothamist.com/2017/07/10/climate_change_ny_mag.php |archivedate=July 10, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/climate-change-earth-too-hot-for-humans.html |title=The Uninhabitable Earth |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 9, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/climate-change-earth-too-hot-for-humans-annotated.html |title=The Uninhabitable Earth, Annotated Edition |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 14, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uninhabitable Earth, The}}\n[[Category:Works originally published in New York (magazine)]]\n[[Category:Global warming media]]\n[[Category:2017 essays]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 magazine article}}\n[[File:The_Uninhabitable_Earth_-_cover.jpg|right|thumb|Cover page of ''The Uninhabitable Earth'']]\n'''\"The Uninhabitable Earth\"''' is a ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine article by American journalist [[David Wallace-Wells]] published on July 9, 2017. The [[Long-form journalism|long-form article]] depicts a [[worst-case scenario]] of what might happen in the near-future due to [[global warming]]. The article starts with the statement \"[i]f your anxiety about global warming is dominated by fears of sea-level rise, you are barely scratching the surface of what terrors are possible.\"  The story was the most read article in the history of the magazine, according to Wallace-Wells.<ref name=\"NYJ\">{{cite web |url=https://journalism.nyu.edu/about-us/event/2017-fall/the-doomed-earth-controversy/ |title=The \u2018Doomed Earth\u2019 Controversy |work=Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute |author=Robert Lee Hotz |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=March 31, 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe article was the inspiration for [[The Uninhabitable Earth (book)|''The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming'']], a book-length treatment of the ideas explored in the original essay.<ref>{{ASIN|B07GVPFH5V}}</ref>\n\n==General==\nOn November 20, 2017, NYUs Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute hosted a 2 hour long conversation between Wallace-Wells and Michael E. Mann to discuss the controversy around the article.<ref name=\"NYJ\"/>\n\nAccompanying the article are a series of extended interviews with scientists. These include paleontologist [[Peter Ward (paleontologist)|Peter Ward]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/what-mass-extinctions-teach-us-about-climate-change-today.html |title=\u2018The Models Are Too Conservative\u2019: Paleontologist Peter Ward on What Past Mass Extinctions Can Teach Us About Climate Change Today |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> climatologist [[Michael E. Mann]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/scientist-michael-mann-on-climate-scenarios.html |title=Scientist Michael Mann on \u2018Low-Probability But Catastrophic\u2019 Climate Scenarios |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]  |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> oceanographer [[Wallace Smith Broecker]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/man-who-coined-global-warming-on-worst-case-scenarios.html |title=The Man Who Coined the Term \u2018Global Warming\u2019 on the Worst-Case Scenario for Planet Earth |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref> climatologist [[James Hansen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/scientist-jim-hansen-the-planet-could-become-ungovernable.html |title=\u2018The Planet Could Become Ungovernable\u2019: Climate Scientist James Hansen on Obama\u2019s Environmental Record, Scientific Reticence, and His Climate Lawsuit Against the Federal Government |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 12, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref> and scientist [[Michael Oppenheimer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/michael-oppenheimer-10-percent-chance-we-meet-paris-targets.html |title=\u2018Personally, I Would Rate the Likelihood of Staying Under Two Degrees of Warming As Under 10 Percent\u2019: Michael Oppenheimer on the \u2018Unknown Unknowns\u2019 of Climate Change |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 13, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref> In addition an annotated edition of the article was published online that includes inline footnotes.\n\nIn February 2019, Wallace-Wells published ''The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming'' ({{ISBN|978-0525576709}}).<ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/books/586541/the-uninhabitable-earth-by-david-wallace-wells/9780525576709/ |title=The Uninhabitable Earth: Life After Warming |publisher=Penguin RandomHouse |author=David Wallace-Wells |isbn=9780525576709 |year=2019 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> The book was excerpted in ''The Guardian''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/feb/02/the-devastation-of-human-life-is-in-view-what-a-burning-world-tells-us-about-climate-change-global-warming |title=\u2018The devastation of human life is in view\u2019: what a burning world tells us about climate change  |work=[[The Guardian]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=February 2, 2019 |accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe story received immediate criticism from the climate change community along two fronts: the piece is too pessimistic; or it contains some factual errors.<ref name=drum>{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/kevin-drum/2017/07/our-approach-to-climate-change-isnt-working-lets-try-something-else/ |title=Our Approach to Climate Change Isn\u2019t Working. Let\u2019s Try Something Else. |work=Mother Jones |author=Kevin Drum |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nRobinson Meyer of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said it is an \"unusually specific and severe depiction of what global warming will do to the planet.\"<ref name=meyer>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/07/is-the-earth-really-that-doomed/533112/ |title=Are We as Doomed as That ''New York'' Magazine Article Says? |work=[[The Atlantic]] |author=Robinson Meyer |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Susan Matthews writing in ''Slate'' said \"The instantly viral piece might be the ''[[Silent Spring]]'' of our time\".<ref name=matthews>{{cite web |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/health_and_science/science/2017/07/we_are_not_alarmed_enough_about_climate_change.html |title=Alarmism Is the Argument We Need to Fight Climate Change |work=Slate |author=Susan Matthews |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe NGO Climate Feedback summarized reviews by dozens of professional scientists and concluded the majority of the reviewers tagged: Alarmist, Imprecise/Unclear, Misleading.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://climatefeedback.org/evaluation/scientists-explain-what-new-york-magazine-article-on-the-uninhabitable-earth-gets-wrong-david-wallace-wells/ |title=Scientists explain what New York Magazine article on \"The Uninhabitable Earth\" gets wrong |work=Climate Feedback |author= |date=July 12, 2017 |accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSome journalists defended the science saying it is mostly correct, \"I haven\u2019t seen any good evidence for serious factual errors,\" said Kevin Drum.<ref name=drum/> Emily Atkin said \"The complaints about the science in Wallace-Wells\u2019s article are mostly quibbles\".<ref name=atkin>{{cite web |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/143788/power-peril-climate-disaster-porn |title=The Power and Peril of \"Climate Disaster Porn\" |work=New Republic |author=Emily Atkin |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe major criticism is that David Wallace-Wells was trying to scare people.<ref name=drum/> This theme was then explored by journalists and commentators with some saying they thought fear was necessary given the reality of the problem, while others thought scaring people was counter-productive.<ref name=meyer/><ref name=matthews/><ref name=drum/><ref name=atkin/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-energy-202/2017/07/11/the-energy-202-trump-could-start-his-infrastructure-push-at-energy-department/59638f59e9b69b7071abcaf2/ |title=The Energy 202: Trump could start his infrastructure push at Energy Department |work=[[Washington Post]] |author=Dino Grandoni |date=July 11, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> For example, [[Eric Holthaus]] said that \"scaring the shit out of [people] is a really bad strategy\" for getting them to want to [[Climate change mitigation|address climate change]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://grist.org/climate-energy/stop-scaring-people-about-climate-change-it-doesnt-work/ |title=Stop scaring people about climate change. It doesn\u2019t work. |work=Grist |author=Eric Holthaus  |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a later interview, David Wallace-Wells said \"it didn\u2019t seem plausible to me that there was more risk at scaring people too much than there was at not scaring them enough ... my feeling was, and is, if there's a one percent chance that we\u2019ve set off a chain reaction that could end the human race, then that should be something that the public knows and thinks about.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=http://gothamist.com/2017/07/10/climate_change_ny_mag.php |title=Are Humans Doomed? A Q&A With The Author Of NY Mag's Terrifying Climate Change Story |work=Gothamist |author=Rebecca Fishbein |date=July 10, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710230334/http://gothamist.com/2017/07/10/climate_change_ny_mag.php |archivedate=July 10, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/climate-change-earth-too-hot-for-humans.html |title=The Uninhabitable Earth |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 9, 2017 |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/07/climate-change-earth-too-hot-for-humans-annotated.html |title=The Uninhabitable Earth, Annotated Edition |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=David Wallace-Wells |date=July 14, 2017 |accessdate=July 14, 2017}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uninhabitable Earth, The}}\n[[Category:Works originally published in New York (magazine)]]\n[[Category:Global warming media]]\n[[Category:2017 essays]]\n", "name_user": "Jlevi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:pipe", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Uninhabitable_Earth"}
{"title_page": "\u013dudov\u00edt Rado", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = \u013dudov\u00edt Rado\n| fullname       = \u013dudov\u00edt Rado\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| height         =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|df=yes|1914|7|27}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bratislava]], [[Kingdom of Bohemia]],<br>[[Cisleithania]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1992|5|23|1914|7|27}}\n| death_place    =\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    =\n| years1         = 193?\u20131936\n| clubs1         = [[DSV Saaz]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1936\u20131939\n| clubs2         = [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1939\u20131944\n| clubs3         = [[\u0160K Slovan Bratislava|\u0160K Bratislava]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1934\u20131938\n| nationalteam1  = [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1940\u20131942\n| nationalteam2  = [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''\u013dudov\u00edt Rado''' (27 July 1914 \u2013 23 May 1992) was a Slovak [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and appeared for both the [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] national teams.<ref name=\"WF\">{{WorldFootball.net}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRado made his international debut for [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] on 25 March 1934 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] match against [[France national football team|France]], which finished as a 2\u20131 win in [[Colombes]]. He earned his second and final [[Cap (sport)|cap]] on 24 April 1938 in a [[1938 FIFA World Cup qualification Group 7|1938 World Cup qualifying]] fixture against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]]. He missed a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in the match, which finished as a 6\u20130 win in [[Prague]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Courtney |first=Barrie |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/38qual.html |title=World Cup 1938 \u2013 Qualifying |work=[[RSSSF]] |date=5 June 2006 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He later represented the [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia national team]], making his first appearance on 6 June 1940 in a friendly against Bulgaria, which finished as a 4\u20131 win in [[Sofia]]. He was capped ten times for Slovakia, making his final appearance on 22 November 1942 in a friendly match against [[Germany national football team|Germany]], which finished as a 2\u20135 loss in [[Bratislava]].<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=17261 |title=\u013dudov\u00edt Rado |website=EU-Football.info |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRado died on 23 May 1992 at the age of 77.<ref name=\"WF\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Team<ref name=\"EUF\"/>!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]\n|1934||1||0\n|-\n|1938||1||0\n|-\n!Total!!2!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]]\n|1940||2||0\n|-\n|1941||4||0\n|-\n|1942||4||0\n|-\n!Total!!10!!0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Career total!!12!!0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FACR player}}\n* {{NFT player}}\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rado, Ludovit}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Bratislava]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak footballers]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovakia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Slovak footballers]]\n[[Category:Slovakia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Dual internationalists (football)]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:DSV Saaz players]]\n[[Category:AC Sparta Prague players]]\n[[Category:\u0160K Slovan Bratislava players]]\n[[Category:Czechoslovak First League players]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = \u013dudov\u00edt Rado\n| fullname       = \u013dudov\u00edt Rado\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| height         =\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|df=yes|1914|7|27}}\n| birth_place    = [[Bratislava]], [[Kingdom of Bohemia]],<br>[[Cisleithania]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1992|5|23|1914|7|27}}\n| death_place    =\n| position       = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| youthyears1    =\n| youthclubs1    =\n| years1         = 193?\u20131936\n| clubs1         = [[DSV Saaz]]\n| caps1          =\n| goals1         =\n| years2         = 1936\u20131939\n| clubs2         = [[AC Sparta Prague|Sparta Prague]]\n| caps2          =\n| goals2         =\n| years3         = 1939\u20131944\n| clubs3         = [[\u0160K Slovan Bratislava|\u0160K Bratislava]]\n| caps3          =\n| goals3         =\n| totalcaps      =\n| totalgoals     =\n| nationalyears1 = 1934\u20131938\n| nationalteam1  = [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1940\u20131942\n| nationalteam2  = [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 10\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n'''\u013dudov\u00edt Rado''' (27 July 1914 \u2013 23 May 1992) was a Slovak [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] and appeared for both the [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] and [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]] national teams.<ref name=\"WF\">{{WorldFootball.net}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRado made his international debut for [[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]] on 25 March 1934 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] match against [[France national football team|France]], which finished as a 2\u20131 win in [[Colombes]]. He earned his second and final [[Cap (sport)|cap]] on 24 April 1938 in a [[1938 FIFA World Cup qualification Group 7|1938 World Cup qualifying]] fixture against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]]. He missed a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]] in the match, which finished as a 6\u20130 win in [[Prague]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Courtney |first=Barrie |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tables/38qual.html |title=World Cup 1938 \u2013 Qualifying |work=[[RSSSF]] |date=5 June 2006 |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> He later represented the [[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia national team]], making his first appearance on 6 June 1940 in a friendly against Bulgaria, which finished as a 4\u20131 win in [[Sofia]]. He was capped ten times for Slovakia, making his final appearance on 22 November 1942 in a friendly match against [[Germany national football team|Germany]], which finished as a 2\u20135 loss in [[Bratislava]].<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=17261 |title=\u013dudov\u00edt Rado |website=EU-Football.info |access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRado died on 23 May 1992 at the age of 77.<ref name=\"WF\"/>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Team<ref name=\"EUF\"/>!!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Czechoslovakia national football team|Czechoslovakia]]\n|1934||1||0\n|-\n|1938||1||0\n|-\n!Total!!2!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Slovakia national football team|Slovakia]]\n|1940||2||0\n|-\n|1941||4||0\n|-\n|1942||4||0\n|-\n!Total!!10!!0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Career total!!12!!0\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FACR player}}\n* {{NFT playe